==Audience polls== * ''[[Seven Samurai]]'' (1954) was voted number one in an audience poll conducted by ''MovieMail'' in 2000. It was followed by ''[[The Third Man]]'' (1949) in second place.<ref name=Lists/> * ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972) was voted number one by ''Entertainment Weekly''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s readers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/ew100.html |title=posting about Entertainment Weekly's book |publisher=Filmsite.org |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> and voted as number one in a ''Time Out'' readers' poll in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/timeout2.html |title=posting about '&#39;Time out'&#39; reader's poll |publisher=Filmsite.org |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> The film was also voted as the "Greatest Movie of All Time" in September 2008 by 10,000 readers of ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine, 150 people from the movie business and 50 film critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/99.asp |title=Empire Online |publisher=Empire Online |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> It currently holds the number 1 spot on the Top 200 at Everyone's a Critic,<ref name="everyone">[http://www.everyonesacritic.net/movie_rank.asp The Top 200] at Everyone's a Critic. Retrieved 2009-10-28</ref> and the number 2 spot on the IMDb list.<ref name="IMDB" /> * ''[[The Godfather Part II]]'' (1974) was voted best movie ever by ''[[TV Guide]]'' readers<ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/tvguide2.html 50 Greatest Movies from TV Guide<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> in 1998, and is currently in third place on the IMDb list.<ref name="IMDB"/> * ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope|Star Wars]]'' (1977) and its sequel ''[[Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back|The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980) were chosen as the greatest films by readers of ''Empire'' magazine in November 2001 and by voters in a [[Channel 4]] ([[Film4]]) poll.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1676023.stm | work=BBC News | title=Star Wars voted best film ever | date=2001-11-26 | accessdate=2010-03-26}}</ref> ''Star Wars'' is also the highest ranking sci-fi film in both versions of the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the 100 greatest movies of all time (ranked number 15 in the [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies|original list]], and number 13 in the [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Movies (10th Anniversary Edition)|updated list]]). * ''[[Raise the Red Lantern]]'' (1991) was voted the best [[Asian cinema|Asian film]] in another audience poll conducted by ''MovieMail'' in 2000. It was followed by ''[[The Apu Trilogy]]'' (1955â1959) at second place.<ref name=Lists/> * ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993) was voted the best film ever made by the German film magazine ''Cinema''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinema.de/news/specials/m/magicmoments?object_id=434&artobj_id=1447 |title=Magische Filmmomente Top 100 Filme anno 2000 News & Specials.Alle Specials |publisher=Cinema.de |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[The Shawshank Redemption]]'' (1994) currently holds the top spot on the [[Internet Movie Database]]'s list of the top 250 films.<ref name="IMDB"/> It was voted the best film not to have won an [[Academy Award]] in a 2004 [[Radio Times]] poll and again in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7261504.stm|title=Shawshank leads Oscar losers poll |publisher=BBC NEWS|accessdate=2009-09-18 | date=2008-02-24}}</ref> It is currently ranked number 1 on [[FilmCrave]].com's top 100 movies list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmcrave.com/list_top_movie.php|title=Official Top Movie List|publisher=filmcrave.com|accessdate=2009-01-14}}</ref> It holds an extremely high score on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] within the community, at 98%. * [[The Lord of the Rings film trilogy|The ''Lord of the Rings'' trilogy]] (2001â2003) was voted the most popular film of all time by an audience poll for the Australian television special ''[[My Favourite Film]]'' and by a poll cast by 120,000 German voters for the TV special "Die besten Filme aller Zeiten" ([[German Language|German]] "The best films of all time").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presseportal.de/pm/7841/623493/kabel_eins/ |title=(german) |publisher=presseportal.de |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> Its first film, ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]'' (2001), was the pick of readers in a poll by ''Empire'' magazine in November 2004.<ref>[http://www.cinemarealm.com/best-of-cinema/empires-500-greatest-movies-of-all-time/ Empire's 500 Greatest Movies of All Time] at cinemarealm.com</ref> The third film, ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'', was voted the best movie of all time by Yahoo movies and Movies.com's annual reader's poll in 2006 and 2007.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} * ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'' (1939) was ranked as the greatest film in a poll surveyed by [[Harris Interactive]] between January 15 and 22, 2008. ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope|Star Wars]]'' came in second place and ''Casablanca'' in third.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harrisinteractive.com/harris_poll/index.asp?PID=874 |title=Harris Poll |publisher=Harrisinteractive.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> ''Gone with the Wind'' was also picked as the best film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/greatest Best in Film - Greatest] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref> * ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' (1942) was voted the greatest film by readers of the ''[[Los Angeles Daily News]]'' in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/dailynews.html |title='&#39;Los Angeles Daily News'&#39; film poll (1997) |publisher=Filmsite.org |date=1997-12-03 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> It is also regarded the "best [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] movie of all time" by the influential ''[[Leonard Maltin]]'s Movie Guide''.<ref>[http://www.filmsite.org/maltin.html 100 Must-See Films Of The 20th Century, Part 1, by Leonard Maltin] at filmsite.org</ref> On April 7, 2006, the Writers' Guild of America declared ''Casablanca''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s screenplay the best ever written.<ref>{{cite web | title = 100 Greatest Screenplays | work = WGAW | url = http://www.wga.org/subpage_newsevents.aspx?id=1807 | accessdate = 2009-09-16}} </ref> * ''[[Cross of Iron]]'' (1977) was voted the greatest film of all time by ''Cinemag''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}
==Particular genres or media== {{Expand list|date=May 2009}}
===Action=== * ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981) was chosen as the best action film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/Action Best in Film - Action] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref> Sites such [[Moviefone]]<ref name="Moviefone">{{cite web | url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2010/01/18/best-action-movies/ | title=The 25 best action movies | publisher=Moviefone.com | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> and [[IGN]] <ref name="IGN">{{cite web | url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/673/673392p5.html | title=The top ten of 25 action films | publisher=[[IGN]] | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> also placed the film as the number one greatest action movie of all time. * ''[[Die Hard]]'' (1988) is also sometimes commonly considered to be one of the greatest action movies ever. <ref name="pajiba">{{cite web | url=http://www.pajiba.com/guides/the-best-action-films-of-all-time.php | title=Die Hard is number one according to Pajiba.com | publisher=Pajiba.com | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> <ref name="Yippie-ki-Yay">{{cite web | url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2009/07/the-50-greatest-action-movies-of-all-time/die-hard | title=Die Hard is the last mentioned on Complex. | publisher=Complex.com | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' voted it the greatest action movie of all time. <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/entertainmentNews/idUSN1448232520070615|title="Die Hard" tops magazine list of best action films|work=[[Reuters]] | date=2007-06-15}}</ref> * ''[[The Terminator]]'' (1984)<ref name="rottenaction"/><ref name="NatFilmReg">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7804404.stm|title=Terminator joins movie archive|date=December 30, 2008 |publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=December 30, 2008}}</ref> along with its sequel ''[[Terminator 2: Judgment Day]]'' (1991),<ref name="pajiba"/><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.filmsite.org/visualeffects7.html | title=Visual and Special Effects Film Milestones | publisher=Filmsite.org | accessdate=2007-07-15}}</ref> ''[[Aliens (film)|Aliens]]'' (1986), <ref name="IGN"/> <ref name="Aliens">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20042607,00.html | title=Aliens is number 2 | publisher=Entertainment Weekly | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> <ref name="rottenaction"/> and ''[[The Matrix]]'' (1999) <ref name="Moviefone"/> are often the highest ranking and most positive reviewed [[science fiction]] action movies. * ''[[Seven Samurai]]'' (1954) is the highest reviewed movie at [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with the highest number of votes that is listed as a [[action movie]] on the site. <ref name="rottenaction">{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt/top_100_action__adventure_movies/?category=1 | title=Rotten Tomatoes best reviewed action movies. | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref>
===Animation=== * ''[[Toy Story]]'' (1995) was voted number 1 on the Top 100 Animated Features of All Time by the [[Online Film Critics Society]] (list published March 2003). <ref>[http://ofcs.rottentomatoes.com/pages/pr/top100animated Top 100 Animated Features of All Time].</ref> The film was also ranked as the greatest animated movie by [[Moviefone]] <ref name="Moviefone 2">{{cite web | url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2008/06/02/feature-page-5-1_m_f/ | title=Best animated movies (5-1) | publisher=Moviefone | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> and ''[[Total Film]]''. <ref name="TFilm">{{cite web | url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-greatest-animated-movies/toy-story-1995 | title=Toy Story is number one. | publisher=''[[Total Film]]'' | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref>''[[Toy Story 2]]'' (1999) topped a Rotten Tomatoes poll of the 50 best animated movies ever made.<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_animated_films/toy_story_2/ Best Animated Films]</ref> It is also number 1 on their list of the best kids movies,<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt_genre.php?category=200002 Best of Kids/Family] at Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved 2009-10-27</ref> and is number 1 on the Movie Review Query Engine's list of the best animated movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/best_cgi_animated_movies |title=MRQE's Best CGI-Animated Movies |publisher=Mrqe.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> Both the original and the sequel currently hold a perfect 100% score at [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name="Toy Story">{{rotten-tomatoes|id=toy_story|title=Toy Story}}</ref><ref name="Toy Story 2">{{rotten-tomatoes|toy_story_2|Toy Story 2}}</ref> * ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]'' (1937) was selected as the best American animated movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their [[AFI's 10 Top 10|10 Top 10]].<ref name="Top 10">{{cite news | publisher = [[American Film Institute]] | title = AFI's 10 Top 10 | date = 2008-06-17 | url = http://www.afi.com/10top10/ | accessdate=2008-11-16}}</ref> * ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (1991) is #1 on the [[IGN]]'s Top 25 Animated Movies of All Time.<ref>Pirrello, Phil; Eric Goldman, Matt Fowler, Scott Collura, Cindy White and Jesse Schedeen. [http://movies.ign.com/articles/650/650717p5.html "Top 25 Animated Movies of All-Time"], ''IGN''</ref> *''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' (1940) was ranked as the number one greatest animated movie by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine.<ref name="Time">{{cite web | url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/23/the-25-all-time-best-animated-films/#pinocchio-1940-2 | title=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/23/the-25-all-time-best-animated-films/#pinocchio-1940-2 | publisher=''[[Time (magazine)]]'' entertainment | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> *''[[WALL-E]]'' (2008) was rankest as the greatest animated movie ever by ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''.<ref name="Wall-E">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20302680_20665319,00.html#20665350 | title=Wall-E is number one. | publisher=Entertainment Weekly | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> *''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]'' (1988) is the highest rated live-action/animated hybrid film on film aggregate [[Rotten Tomatoes]], and has scored an almost perfect rating of 98%. <ref name="Who Framed Roger Rabbit">{{rotten-tomatoes|id=who_framed_roger_rabbit|title=Who Framed Roger Rabbit}}</ref> The film was also ranked as the best [[Films with live action and animation|animated/live action]] hybrid film by ''Entertainment Weekly''. <ref name="live action/animated">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20478386_20930713,00.html#20930680 | title=Who Framed Roger Rabbit is number 1 | publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=November 02, 2011}}</ref> * ''[[The Lion King]]'' (1994) was chosen as the best animated film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/animated Best in Film - Animated] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref> * ''[[What's Opera, Doc?]]'' (1957) was voted the greatest as the greatest [[animated short]] by animators, film historians and directors, in [[Jerry Beck]]'s 1994 poll of [[The 50 Greatest Cartoons]].<ref>[[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]] (ed.) (1994). ''[[The 50 Greatest Cartoons]]: As Selected by 1,000 Animation Professionals''. Atlanta: Turner Publishing.</ref> *Japanese films such as ''[[Spirited Away]]'' (2001),<ref name="TF">{{cite web | url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-greatest-animated-movies/spirited-away-2001 | title=Spirited Away is number 2 | publisher=''Total Film'' | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/06/23/the-25-all-time-best-animated-films/#spirited-away-2001 | title=Spirited Away is the highest anime movie on Time magazine. | publisher=''[[Time (magazine)]]'' | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref><ref name="EW">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20302680_20665319,00.html#2066 | title=Spirited Away as number 2 | publisher=Entetainment Weekly | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> ''[[Akira (film)|Akira]]'' (1988)<ref name="Akira">{{cite web | url=http://www.moviecricket.com/top-10-anime-movies-time-34075/ | title=Akira as number one anime movie. | publisher=Movie Cricket | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> <ref name="Akira 2">{{cite web | url=http://www.screenjunkies.com/movies/movie-lists/10-best-anime-movies-of-all-time/ | title=Ten best anime movies of all time. | publisher=Screen Junkies | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref>and ''[[My Neighbor Totoro]]'' (1988) are commonly considered as one of the greatest [[anime]] films ever and even as one of the greatest animated movies as well.<ref name="Totoro">{{cite web | url=http://www.timeout.com/film/features/show-feature/8866/ | title=My neighbor Totoro is number one by Time Out. | publisher=''[[Time Out (company)|Time Out]]'' | accessdate=November 03, 2011}}</ref> * The Russian animated films, ''[[Tale of Tales (film)|Tale of Tales]]'' and the ''[[Hedgehog in the Fog]]'' by [[Yuri Norshtein]] have been voted as the greatest animated films ever in particular festivals. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.4/articles/deneroffini1.4.html |title=The Olympiad of Animation: An Interview With Fini Littlejohn |author=Harvey Deneroff|publisher=Animation World Magazine |date= |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref>
===Christmas=== * ''[[A Christmas Story]]'' (1983) is [[AOL]]'s number 1 Christmas movie of all time<ref>{{cite web| url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2009/11/04/feature-page-5-1/ |title=Best Christmas Movies (5-1) |publisher=AOL moviefone |accessdate=2011-03-20}}</ref> and [[IGN]]'s top holiday-themed movie of all time.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/670/670493p5.html |title=Top 25 Holiday Movies of All-Time |publisher=[http://www.ign.com/ IGN.com] |accessdate=2011-03-20}}</ref> * ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'' (1946) is number 1 on the Movie Review Query Engine's list of the best holiday movies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/best_holiday_movies |title=MRQE's Best Holiday Movies |publisher=Mrqe.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> and also topped [[AFI's 100 Yearsâ¦100 Cheers]] list.<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/cheers.aspx]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> * ''[[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]'' (1993) is ranked number 1 on ''Rotten Tomatoes''' Top 25 Best Christmas Movies list.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Nightmare Before Christmas (1993): Rank 1 | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_christmas_movies/nightmare_before_christmas/ | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | date = | accessdate = 2008-12-20}}</ref> *''[[Die Hard]]'' (1988) was voted [[Empire Magazine]]'s "The Greatest Christmas Film of All Time" in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p30|title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever|publisher=Empireonline.com|accessdate=2011-04-26}}</ref> and the fourth best in [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' list.<ref>{{cite web | title = Die Hard (1988): Rank 4 | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_christmas_movies/die_hard// | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | date = | accessdate = 2010-04-29}}{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>
===Comedy=== * ''[[Airplane!]]'' (1980) was also chosen as the best comedy for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/comedy Best in Film - Comedy] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref> * ''[[Dr. Strangelove|Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb]]'' (1964) is the highest reviewed comedy movie at [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with a perfect score of 100%.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb'' on rottentomatoes.com | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/browser.php?movietype=3&genre=200003&tomatometer=%3D100%25s&avgrating=&numreviews=&mpaa=}}</ref> It also has a [[Metacritic]] score of 96/100, one of the website's highest rated comedy movies.<ref>http://www.metacritic.com/browse/movies/score/metascore/all?sort=desc&view=detailed</ref> * ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'' (1975) A 2004 poll by UK arm of Amazon and the Internet Movie Database named Monty Python and the Holy Grail as the best British comedy picture of all time.<ref name="Brit's Best Comedy" /> * ''[[Monty Python's Life of Brian]]'' (1979) was voted the greatest comedy ever in polls conducted by [[Total Film]] magazine in 2000,<ref>{{cite news|title=Life of Brian tops comedy poll|publisher= BBC News|date=September 29, 2000 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/948331.stm|accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> the British TV networks [[Channel 4]] in 2006 <ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4573444.stm | work=BBC News | title=Life of Brian named best comedy | date=2006-01-01 | accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> and [[Five (TV channel)|Channel Five]] in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.five.tv/programmes/greatestevermovies/countdown/?list=0|title=Channel Five "Greatest Ever Movies - Comedy"|accessdate=2008-10-09}}</ref> and [[The Guardian]] newspaper in 2007.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://film.guardian.co.uk/features/featurepages/0,,2131880,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=The last laugh: your favourite 50 | first=Philip | last=French | date=2007-07-22 | accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> * ''[[National Lampoon's Animal House]]'' (1978) was voted number 1 on the [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]] list of funniest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.listsofbests.com/list/7092 |title=Bravo's "100 Funniest Movies" on Lists of Bests |publisher=Listsofbests.com |date=2006-06-02 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Some Like It Hot]]'' (1959) was listed Best American Film Comedy by the [[American Film Institute]] in June 2000.<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/laughs.aspx]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> * ''[[City Lights]]'' (1931) was selected as the best [[romantic comedy]] ever by the American Film Institute during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/>
===Comicbook/Superhero=== * ''[[Persepolis (film)|Persepolis]]'' (2007) is number 1 in the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] countdown of movies based on superheroes, graphic novels, manga and comic strips â in order of critical approval. ''[[Iron Man (film)|Iron Man]]'' was also the highest rated [[superhero film]] based on a comic in the list being at #2. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/comics_and_graphic_novels_vs_the_critics/12/|title=Comics and Graphic Novel vs. The Critic|accessdate=July 30, 2010}}</ref> * ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008) is number 1 on the Movie Review Query Engine's list of the best comic and superhero movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/best_comic_book_movies |title=MRQE's Best of Comics & Superheroes |publisher=Mrqe.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' (2004) is number 1 on Rotten Tomatoes' Comix Worst to Best list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/features/special/2007/comic/?r=1&mid=1133520|title=Comix Worst to Best|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|year=2007}}</ref> * ''[[X2 (film)|X2]]'' (2003) was voted number 1 in Empire Magazine's list of the 20 Greatest Comic Book Movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/comicbookfilms/1.asp |title=Empire Features |publisher=Empireonline.com |date=2006-12-05 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[The Incredibles]]'' (2004) was ranked number 1 in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of top ten greatest superhero films.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2075455_2075373_2075286,00.html | title=Time magazine's number one pick. | publisher=''[[Time (magazine)]]''| accessdate=June 7, 2011 | author=Cruz, Gilbert}}</ref> *''[[Superman (film)|Superman]]'' (1978) was ranked number 1 out of IGN's list of 25 greatest superhero films of all time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/676/676647p5.html | title=Top 25 Superhero Films of all-Time pt. 5 | publisher=IGN | accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>
===Courtroom=== * ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (film)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]'' (1962) was selected as the best [[courtroom drama]] ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their [[AFI's 10 Top 10|10 Top 10]] list.<ref name="Top 10"/>
===Crime/Gangster=== * ''[[The Godfather]]'' (1972) was selected as the best gangster movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/> It also tops the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] list of the best drama movies.<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt_genre.php?category=200004 Best of Drama] at Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved 2009-10-27</ref> * ''[[Goodfellas]]'' (1990) was chosen as the greatest crime film out of the 25 movies by the [[IGN]] website.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/664/664641p5.html |title=Top 25 Crime Movies of All-Time |publisher=[http://www.ign.com/ IGN.com] |accessdate=2011-03-20}}</ref>
===Disaster=== * ''[[The Poseidon Adventure (1972 film)|The Poseidon Adventure]]'' (1972) was voted best disaster movie in a poll commissioned by UCI cinemas in May 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3720347.stm |title=Poseidon Adventure tops film poll |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-05-17 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref>
===Documentary=== * ''[[Bowling for Columbine]]'' (2002), [[Michael Moore]]'s controversial documentary relating gun control and the [[culture of fear]] in the United States, heads the list of 20 all-time favorite non-fiction films selected by members of the International Documentary Association (IDA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.cwu.edu/media/intnationaldoc20.htm |title=International Documentary Association Top Twenty Documentaries of All-Time|publisher=Central Washington University -- Brooks Library (at Archive.org)|accessdate=2009-09-18 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080213002531/http://www.lib.cwu.edu/media/intnationaldoc20.htm |archivedate = 2008-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/library/weekly/aabowlingawardnews.htm|title="Bowling for Columbine" Named Best Documentary Film|date=December 12, 2002|publisher=About.com|accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref> * ''[[Seven Up!]]'' (1964) was voted as the greatest ever documentary in a [[Channel 4]] poll of the 50 Greatest Documentaries in 2005.<ref>Dirks, Tim. [http://www.filmsite.org/greatfilmssummary2.html "Top Films of All-Time, Part 2"], [[Filmsite]], 2010.</ref> * ''[[The Last Waltz]]'' (1978) is considered one of the greatest concert documentaries ever created, and has been deemed as such by ''[[Total Film]]'',<ref name = "Total">{{cite web | title = DVD Reviews: The Last Waltz | publisher = Total Film | url = http://www.totalfilm.com/dvd_reviews/the_last_waltz | accessdate = 2007-01-07}}</ref> Michael Worthington of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'',<ref name = "Wilmington">{{cite news | last = Wilmington | first = Michael | title = Movie review, 'The Last Waltz' | publisher = Chicago Tribune | url = http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-16264_lgcy,0,6333653.story | accessdate = 2007-01-07 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080120172929/http://metromix.chicagotribune.com/movies/mmx-16264_lgcy,0,6333653.story |archivedate = January 20, 2008}}</ref> and by Rotten Tomatoes, where it holds a 97% favorable rating.<ref name = "Rotten Tomatoes">{{cite web | title = The Last Waltz | publisher = Rotten Tomatoes | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/last_waltz/?beg=0&int=27&creamcrop_limit=13&page=all | accessdate = 2007-01-08}}</ref> * ''[[The Thin Blue Line (film)|The Thin Blue Line]]'' won Best Documentary honors from the [[New York Film Critics Circle Awards|New York Film Critics Circle]], the [[Kansas City Film Critics Circle]], the [[National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|National Board of Review]], and the [[National Society of Film Critics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0096257/awards |title=The Thin Blue Line (1988) - Awards |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref> Director [[Errol Morris]] himself won an [[International Documentary Association]] Award, an [[Edgar Award]], and a [[MacArthur Fellowship]] Genius Grant (1989).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001554/awards |title=Errol Morris - Awards |publisher=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.documentary.org/awards2009 |title=IDA Documentary Awards 2009 - International Documentary Association |accessdate=2010-06-25}}</ref>
===Epic=== * ''[[Lawrence of Arabia (film)|Lawrence of Arabia]]'' (1962) was voted best epic by readers of ''Total Film'' in May 2004. It was selected as the best epic movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/>
===Fantasy=== * ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'' (2003) is number 1 on the list of the top rated fantasy titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/fantasy Top Rated "Fantasy" Titles] on IMDb. Retrieved 2010-02-23</ref> It is the only film in the genre to win the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. It also won 11 [[Academy Awards]], the highest number of any film ever made (tying with ''Ben-Hur'' and ''Titanic''). It is also the only film in history having won Best Film awards from both [[Academy Award for Best Film|Academy]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|BAFTA]], [[Empire Award for Best Film|Empire]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture - Drama|Golden Globe]], [[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation|Hugo]], [[MTV Movie Award for Best Movie|MTV]], and [[Saturn Award for Best Fantasy Film|Saturn Awards]]. * ''[[The Wizard of Oz (film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (1939) was selected as the best American fantasy movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/> * The [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]] has received critical acclaim for all eight of its installments and has received many awards as well as nominations. It is currently the [[List of highest-grossing film series|highest grossing film series]] of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/world/|title=All Time Worldwide Box Office Grosses|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>
===Horror/Thriller=== * ''[[The Thing (1982)|The Thing]]'' (1982) ranks #1 on ''[[The Boston Globe]]'''s list of the 50 scariest movies of all time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/gallery/top_50_scary_movies?pg=51|title=Top 50 Scariest Horror Movies|publisher=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=4 August 2011 | date=2011-10-25}}</ref> * ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980) ranks number 1 on ''[[The Moving Arts Film Journal]]'''s list of the 25 greatest horror films.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://themovingarts.com/tmas-25-greatest-horror-movies-of-all-time|title=TMA's 25 Greatest Horror Movies of All Time |publisher=[[The Moving Arts Film Journal]]|accessdate=4 August 2010 | date=2010-08-25}}</ref> * ''[[The Exorcist (film)|The Exorcist]]'' (1973) was voted scariest movie of all time by ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' and ''[[Movies.com]]'',{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} and by viewers of AMC in 2006.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2006-10-23|title=AMC Poll: The Exorcist Scariest Movie|publisher=Multichannel News|url=http://www.multichannel.com/article/CA6384063.html|accessdate=2008-11-30}}</ref> It was also chosen as the best horror film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/Horror Best in Film - Horror] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref> * ''[[Psycho (film)|Psycho]]'' (1960). The [[Alfred Hitchcock]] classic tops [[American Film Institute|AFI]]'s list of the 100 most thrilling American films,<ref name="100 thrills">{{cite news | publisher = [[American Film Institute]] | title = AFI's 100 years... 100 thrills | year = 2001 | url = http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/thrills100.pdf?docID=250 | accessdate=2009-12-07}}</ref> and the top rated horror titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/horror Top Rated "Horror" Titles] at IMDb. Retrieved 2009-10-26</ref> * ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'' (1933) is currently number 1 on the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] list of the best horror movies,<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt_genre.php?category=10 Best of Horror] at Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved 2010-07-25</ref> and topped the Rotten Tomatoes list of the 50 best horror movies of all time.<ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_horror_movies/1011615-king_kong/ Rotten Tomatoes: Best Horror Movies] Retrieved 2010-03-17</ref> * ''[[Jaws (film)|Jaws]]'' (1975) was number one in the Bravo network's five-hour miniseries ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]'' in 2004.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20060830052813/http://www.bravotv.com/The_100_Scariest_Movie_Moments/index.shtml The 100 Scariest Movie Moments], BravoTV.com at archive.org</ref> It was also ranked second on [[American Film Institute|AFI]]'s list for thrillers, ''[[100 Years... 100 Thrills]]''. It holds a rare 100% "Fresh" rating on the review aggregate website [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jaws/ |title=Jaws Movie Reviews, Pictures |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |date= |accessdate=2011-07-12}}</ref> * ''[[The Texas Chain Saw Massacre]]'' (1974) ranks number 1 on ''[[Total Film]]'''s list of the greatest horror films.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4323968.stm|title=Texas Massacre tops horror poll |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=22 November 2009 | date=2005-10-09}}</ref> * ''[[The Silence of the Lambs (film)|The Silence of the Lambs]]'' (1991) was chosen as the best suspense/thriller for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/thriller Best in Film - Thriller] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref>
===Musical=== * ''[[A Hard Day's Night (film)|A Hard Day's Night]]'' (1964) is ranked number 1 on both [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' lists of the Top Ten Certified Fresh Musicals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/grease/news/1889976/5/rts_top_ten_certified_fresh_musicals/|title=RT's Top Ten Certified Fresh Musicals|author=Tim Ryan, Jeff Giles, Ryan Fujitani, David Chung, Luke Goodsell, and Alex Vo|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|date=6 July 2010|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> and the Best Reviewed Movies of All Time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/best_reviewed_movies/beatles_a_hard_days_night/ | title=Best Reviewed Movies of All Time - A Hard Day's Night|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=7 July 2010}}</ref> * ''[[Singin' in the Rain (film)|Singin' in the Rain]]'' (1952) tops the American Film Institute's list of the 25 best American musicals of all time,<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/musicals.aspx 25 Best Musicals]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> and the top rated musicals at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/musical Top Rated "Musical" Titles] at IMDb. Retrieved 2009-10-26</ref> * ''[[West Side Story (film)|West Side Story]]'' (1961) was chosen as the best screen musical by readers of ''[[The Observer]]'' in a 2007 poll.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2007/02/19/west_side_story_tops_best_movie_musical_/ |title=West Side Story Tops Best Movie Musical |publisher=Starpulse.com |date=2007-02-19 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' (1965) was chosen as the best musical for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/Musical Best in Film - Musical] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref>
===Mystery=== * ''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954) is currently number 1 on the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] list of the best mystery/suspense films.<ref name="rottenmystery">[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt_genre.php?category=13 Best of Mystery/Suspense] at Rotten Tomatoes. Retrieved 2010-07-25</ref> * ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958) was selected as the best mystery movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/>
===Political/Historical=== * ''[[Schindler's List]]'' (1993) was chosen as the best political/historical film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/political Best Film - Political] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref>
===Propaganda=== * ''[[The Battleship Potemkin]]'' (1925) has been called one of the most influential [[propaganda film]]s of all time,<ref name=review1>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcritic.com/reviews/1925/battleship-potemkin/|title=Battleship Potemkin|accessdate=2010-11-28}}</ref> and was named the greatest film of all time at the [[Expo 58|Brussels World's Fair]] in 1958.<ref name="Potem">[http://www.film.com/features/story/whats-big-deal-battleship-potemkin/42684110 What's the Big Deal?: Battleship Potemkin (1925)]. Retrieved November 28, 2010.</ref><ref name=EbertFest>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebertfest.com/one/battleship_rev.htm|title=Battleship Potemkin by Roger Ebert|accessdate=2010-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/greatfilmssummary.html|title=Top Films of All-Time|accessdate=2010-11-28}}</ref> * ''[[Triumph of the Will]]'' (1935), [[Leni Riefenstahl]]'s documentary film glorifying [[Adolf Hitler]] and the 1934 [[Nazi Party]] [[Political convention|Convention]], in [[Nuremberg]] is widely perceived, renowned and acknowledged as the best [[propaganda]] film ever,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/international/story/0,3604,1039001,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Leni Riefenstahl, Hitler's favourite film propagandist, dies at 101 | first=Luke | last=Harding | date=2003-09-10 | accessdate=2010-05-02}}</ref> although Riefenstahl asserted she intended it only as a documentary.
===Religious=== * In 1996, the [[Holy See]] released three lists of recommended films. The three different lists considered films of religious value, virtue (or moral value) and artistic merit. Among the list of 15 religious films considered by the Vatican to be the best ever, were in no particular order, [[William Wyler]]'s ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'', ''[[The Mission (1986 film)|The Mission]]'', ''[[The Passion of Joan of Arc]]'', and [[Fred Zinnemann]]'s 1966 version of ''[[A Man for All Seasons (1966 film)|A Man For All Seasons]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinepad.com/vatican.htm |title=The Vatican Movie List |publisher=Cinepad.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[The Island (2006 film)|The Island]]'' (2006) about [[Russian Orthodox]] monks living together on a remote, [[Arctic]] island, garnered multiple awards. 2006: best film at the Moscow Premiere festival. 2007: Six awards at the fifth national [[Golden Eagle Awards]]: "Best film", "Best male support role" ([[Viktor Suhorukov]]), "Best male role" ([[Petr Mamonov]]), "Best director" ([[Pavel Lungin]]), "Best scenario" (Dmitry Sobolev), "Best operator work" (Andrei Zhegalov). 2007: [[Nika Award]]s for Best Picture, Best Director, Best Actor, Best Supporting Actor, etc.
===Romance=== * ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' (1942) was voted the top romantic American film on [[AFI's 100 Years... 100 Passions]] list,<ref>[http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/passions.aspx]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> and is currently number 1 on the top rated romance titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/romance Top Rated "Romance" Titles] at IMDb. Retrieved 2009-10-26</ref> * ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo & Juliet]]'' (1968) is currently #1 on DigitalDreamDoor.com's list of the 100 Greatest Romance Movies.<ref>[http://digitaldreamdoor.nutsie.com/pages/movie-pages/movie_romance.html]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>
===Science fiction===<!-- This section is linked from [[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)]] --> * See ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope|Star Wars]]'', in the [[#Audience polls|Films acclaimed in audience polls]] section above. * ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968) tops the [[Online Film Critics Society]] list of greatest science fiction films of all time.<ref>{{cite web | title=''2001: A Space Odyssey'' Named the Greatest Sci-Fi Film of All Time By the Online Film Critics Society | publisher=Online Film Critics Society | url=http://ofcs.rottentomatoes.com/pages/pr/top100scifi | accessdate=2006-12-15}}{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> It is also the only science fiction film to make the [[Sight and Sound]] poll for ten best movies, and was selected as the best science fiction movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their [[AFI's 10 Top 10|10 Top 10]].<ref name="Top 10"/> * ''[[Blade Runner]]'' (1982) was voted the best science fiction film by a panel of scientists assembled by the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alok Jha, science correspondent |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk_news/story/0,3604,1290823,00.html |title=Scientists vote Blade Runner best sci-fi film of all time |publisher=Guardian |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> In ''[[New Scientist]]'', ''Blade Runner'' was voted "all-time favourite science fiction film" in both the staff,<ref>{{cite web|work=New Scientist|title=New Scientist's favourite sci-fi film |url=http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn14805-new-scientists-favourite-scifi-film-.html|first = Alison | last = George |date=1 October 2008|publisher=Reed Business Information|accessdate=2008-11-28}}</ref> and reader's 2008 polls.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=New Scientist|title=Sci-fi special: Your all-time favourite science fiction|url=http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20026826.300-scifi-special-your-alltime-favourite-science-fiction.html|issue=2682|first = Alison | last = George |date=12 November 2008|publisher=Reed Business Information}}</ref> * ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial]]'' (1982) topped a [[Rotten Tomatoes]] poll of the 100 best Science Fiction movies ever made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/features/special/2007/scifi/?r=1&mid=1006389 |title=ET named top Sci-Fi Movie |publisher=Rottentomatoes.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back|Star Wars: Episode V - The Empire Strikes Back]]'' (1980) was voted number one in [[Total Film]]'s Top 100 Movies of All Time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/total_film_presents_the_top_100_movies_of_all_time |title=Total Film Presents the Top 100 Movies of All Time |publisher=Totalfilm.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> and number one in the 2006 Empire "Greatest Movies Ever" special.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} It is currently number 2 on the top rated sci-fi titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref name="IMDB Sci-Fi">[http://www.imdb.com/chart/scifi Top Rated "Sci-Fi" Titles] at IMDb. Retrieved 2009-10-26</ref>
===Sports=== * ''[[Murderball (film)|Murderball]]'' (2005) is number 1 on the [[Rotten Tomatoes]] countdown of the top sports movies.<ref>{{cite web| title = Top Sports Movies | publisher = Rotten Tomatoes | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/guides/top_sports/murderball/| accessdate = 2010-08-09}}</ref> * ''[[Raging Bull]]'' (1980) was selected as the best sports movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their [[AFI's 10 Top 10|10 Top 10]],<ref name="Top 10"/> and is currently number 1 on the top rated sport titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/sport Top Rated "Sport" Titles] at the Internet Movie Database. Retrieved 2009-10-26</ref> * ''[[Miracle (film)|Miracle]]'' (2004) is currently standing as the overall best sports movie of all time in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/ |title=Sports Movies : Sports Films and DVDs Guide |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Cinderella Man]]'' (2005) is currently standing as the best [[boxing]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/boxing.asp |title=Best Boxing Movies : Top Boxing Movies : Official Poll by Sports Movies Guide |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Le Mans (film)|Le Mans]]'' (1971) is currently standing as the best [[auto racing]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/auto-racing.asp |title=Best Auto Racing Movies - Polls & Rankings |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Bull Durham]]'' (1988) is currently standing as the best [[baseball]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/baseball.asp |title=Best Baseball Movies : Top Baseball Movies : Official Poll by Sports Movies Guide |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Coach Carter]]'' (2005) is currently standing as the best [[basketball]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/basketball.asp |title=Best Basketball Movies : Top Basketball Movies : Official Poll by Sports Movies Guide |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Caddyshack]]'' (1980) is currently standing as the best [[golf]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/golf.asp |title=Best Golf Movies : Top Golfing Movies : Official Poll by Sports Movies Guide |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Chariots of Fire]]'' (1981) is currently standing as the best [[track and field]] movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/track-field.asp |title=Best Track & Field Movies - Top Track & Field Movies - Best Running Movies |publisher=Sportsinmovies.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Brian's Song]]'' is the currently the top rated American football movie in the ongoing poll at sportsinmovies.com<ref>{{cite web|title=Best Football Movies|url=http://www.sportsinmovies.com/best-movies/football.asp|work=Sportsinmovies.com}}</ref>
===War=== * See ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]'', ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' and ''[[Schindler's List]]'' in the [[#Audience polls|Films acclaimed in audience polls]] section above. * ''[[Paths of Glory]]'' (1957) is number 1 on the Movie Review Query Engine's list of the best military movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/best_military_movies |title=MRQE's Best Military Movies |publisher=Mrqe.com |date=1993-10-03 |accessdate=2011-08-04}}</ref> * ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'' (1998) was voted as the greatest war film in a 2008 [[Channel 4]] poll of the 100 greatest war films.<ref>{{cite web| title = 100 Greatest War Films| publisher = Channel4.com| url = http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/W/greatest_warfilms/results/5-1.html| accessdate = 2008-04-02}}{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref> * ''[[The Longest Day (film)|The Longest Day]]'' (1962) topped the list of the [[Moviefone]] 25 Best War Movies.<ref>{{cite web| title = 25 Best War Movies| publisher = moviefone.com| url = http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/03/07/feature-page-5-1-films/| accessdate = 2011-06-02}}</ref> * ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'' (1979) was the second rated war movie of all time based on the Movifone list (after ''Schindler's List'') and the [[IMDB]] War movie list (after ''The Longest Day'').<ref>{{cite web| title = Top Rated War Titles| publisher = imdb.com| url = http://www.imdb.com/chart/war| accessdate = 2011-06-02}}</ref> It is ranked number 1 on [[Channel 4]]'s ''[[50 Films To See Before You Die]]''.
===Western=== * ''[[The Searchers (film)|The Searchers]]'' (1956) was selected as the best western movie ever by the [[American Film Institute]] during their 10 Top 10.<ref name="Top 10"/> (See also: [[#Films acclaimed by critics and filmmakers|films acclaimed by critics and filmmakers]] above). * ''[[The Good, the Bad and the Ugly]] (Il buono, il brutto, il cattivo)'' (1966). Currently number 1 on the top rated western titles at the [[Internet Movie Database]].<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/chart/western Top Rated "Western" Titles] at IMDb. Retrieved 2010-09-20</ref> * ''[[Once Upon a Time in the West]]'' (1968). [[Empire Magazine]] ranks the film on its poll of "500 Greatest Movies of All Time" at number 14, the highest ranking Western. * ''[[Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid]]'' (1969) was chosen as the best western film for [[Best in Film: The Greatest Movies of Our Time]].<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Best_Film/Western Best in film - Western] Retrieved 2011-03-24</ref>
